ce:section.ce:para:
Raw cells 264.7 are tumor cells induced by leukemia in mice, belonging to the peritoneal macrophages cell line of mice, which is one of the commonly used inflammatory cell models. Enormous number of evidences showed that, in the pathogenesis of IBD especially in chronic disease CD, abnormally activated macrophages could secrete a large amount of proinflammatory cytokine tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-α) [36]. Therefore, activated macrophages could be used as in vitro inflammatory models to study the targeting potential of CDs/Man-NPs nanocomposite. Lipopolysaccharides (LPS), an essential component of gram-negative bacteria outer membrane, could stimulate and activate macrophages to secrete proinflammatory cytokines [37]. After treated with LPS (1000 ng/mL), the activated macrophages secreted significant amounts of TNF-α (2105.78 pg/mg protein) (Fig. 5
                        ). This was about twenty times more than untreated groups (101.30 pg/mg), confirming the inflammation in the in vitro model. These results were according to the report by Wilson. [38]. The untreated and activated macrophages were used to evaluate whether the inflammation could affect the cellular uptake of CDs/Man-NPs nanocomposite. Here, the internalized CDs/Man-NPs (blue fluorescence) were located in the periphery of the cytoplasm and nucleus (Fig. 6
                        ). Whereas, more reliable fluorescent signals were detected in the cytoplasm of activated macrophages than that in untreated macrophages. This might be related to overexpression of the mannose receptor on the surface of the activated macrophage. However, the cellular uptake after LPS stimulation was significantly higher than that of the groups without stimulation. In pathological condition; the macrophages were under very active processes of phagocytosis and exocytosis. While, macrophages offered the dual benefactions of mannose-MR binding and higher NPs favorable uptake, leading to selective and specific targeting to the inflammation sites [31]. When the activated macrophages incubated with CDs/Man-NPs nanocomposite and unmodified nanocomposite (CDs/NPs), respectively, the higher fluorescent signal was observed in CDs/Man-NPs nanocomposite groups. After adding the free mannose solution into serum-free medium containing CDs/Man-NPs nanocomposite, the fluorescence became weaker due to competitive inhibition [39]. Moreover, when CDs/Man-NPs nanocomposite was incubated with 4T1 cells (mannose receptor-negative cell line), no apparent fluorescent signal was observed. These findings suggested that the recognition of CDs/Man-NPs nanocomposite to macrophages was targeted and selective due to receptor-ligand interactions [25]. Remarkably the steady labelling efficiency of CDs in the CDs/Man-NPs nanocomposite about 21.6%, the quantitative test was directly analyzed according to the fluorescence intensity in the intracellular fluid. The quantitative determination (Fig. 7A-D) of cellular uptake further verified the results detected by fluorescence microscope. In conclusion, these results indicated that CDs/Man-NPs nanocomposite could be effectively internalized into the inflamed macrophages via ligand-receptor mediate.
